	Off the strip but a nice place	I've been to the Palms on business many times, but this was the first time that I stayed here. I have previously stayed across the street at the Rio or Gold Coast. I guess my travel department got a good rate, so they put me here on this trip.The bed was comfortable, HD tv in the room, bathroom nice. No complaints about the amenities. This hotel is located off the strip, but there is plenty to do, even if you do not want to walk out to the hotels across the street or travel down to the strip. There are several trendy clubs here (including the Playboy club). Clubbing is not my scene, and paying $20 for a Ketel One is outrageous, but hey, you are in Vegas! There is a fantastic view from the clubs, as they are located at the top of the hotel, so that's worth it.The restaurants are all OK... I like the the Mexican one, the cafe has slow service, but the food's OK. The best value here is the buffet. It's smaller than some of the strip hotel buffet's but there's enough of a selection of tasty food to satisfy anyone.There's also a food court and a frozen yogurt stand (similar to Pinkberry in NYC; you serve yourself however much you want, put on whatever toppings you want, and pay per ounce.) There's also a movie theatre in the hotel, so if you have had enough of the tables and shows, you can catch a flick. I think the Palms caters to a younger crowd than some of the other strip hotels I have been to.I haven't stayed here previously because the room rate was higher than comparable hotels, and my travel department would not pay the difference. However, if you can get into the Palms at a good rate, it is definitely worth it. With all the Vegas hotels vying for your business now, there are good buys to be had. The Palms is not worth paying a premium for, as if it was the creme de la creme like Wynn or Bellagio, but at the the right price, it's a great deal.	
