Jan 12 2009	Perfect	I got a great rate on hotels.com albeit for a basic room. We arrived late (9pm) after a long drive from LA about 10 days before Xmas for a Sunday and Monday night stay. I visit Vegas a lot but had never stayed at the Plams and was looking forward to it. At checkin, I tried the $20 trick and asked for a room in the Fantasy Tower if possible. All sorted and a nice high room looking towards Mandaly Bay end of the strip. The decor of the room was very nice, modern, massive Plasma TV with HD. The bathroom was very large although no separate shower, but the bath was massive. The jacuzzi jets didn't work. The problem with Vegas hotels is you often park and it's a long trudge to the room. It was literally less than 3 minutes, car parked to your room. I have never been able to park so close before. I would rate this a 4.5 due to the tub not working, and lack of separate shower but I got such a crazy rate ($20 a night) I had to rate it a 5*The buffet is dirt cheap by Vegas standards. You can get breakfast for about $8 whereas you would be lucky to get a breakie for that in some dive.	
Jan 1 2009 	Stayed here many times - not coming back	I love Las Vegas and have stayed at The Palms my last three trips there. I stay at The Palms for a few reasons: first I'm in my early 20s and I like that it's mainly a hotel for people my age. Second, I've found that drunks leaving their clubs tend to lose a lot of money at poker, and it's more concentrated at The Palms than at other casinos in Vegas. Third, they used to treat me well. Lastly, the rooms are nice (flat screen tvs, jacuzzi tub, huge bathrooms, comfortable bed).In addition, the food is very good. N9ne is one of my favorite restaurants (not just in Vegas, but in general), and the views from Nove are great. But, I wouldn't consider the food a reason to stay at the hotel because anyone can come and go to restaurants as he/she pleases. Also, because they're owned by the Maloofs, you can find some odds on sporting events that are different here than other hotels in Vegas - another plus.My most recent trip to Vegas was in Oct 2008, and I went with a colleague of mine. We each brought our golf clubs and was looking forward to a great round of golf. Limo brought us from the airport to the hotel - nobody opened the door for us, even though we had luggage and clubs. We decided to leave the clubs with the bell desk rather than take them upstairs to the room, and they accommodated us. Two days later, we went golfing, got our clubs no problem, went golfing, came back, same story - no doorman. We left the clubs with the bell desk again, bellman told us he'd put the clubs back in our travel cases for us (we tipped him an extra 10 bucks for his efforts) and the following day come checkout, the clubs weren't in the bags for us.In addition, the dealers were rude, and significantly worse than at other hotels. The maid didn't clean our room the first night until we called at 4pm the next day. The poker games dried up. Many regulars know that The Palms attracts drunks who lose at poker, and they flood the tables during late night. The room doesn't spread a wide variety of games, and doesn't attract that many players.The sportsbook is still good. The odds are competitive and the staff is friendly. They even added a betting option upon my request.The casino is small, but sufficient. The Playboy Club shouldn't charge a cover, but they do and it's too expensive. It's a Playboy themed high limit casino, and frankly nobody should be charged money to play high limit blackjack or roulette and give up house edge.The other clubs are expensive as well. I'm not a club person, but I really enjoyed Moon. The lines downstairs are too long, and too slow, so you either have to get put on a list or pay the bouncer to let you in. My buddy just talked to him and we jumped the line.Full disclosure - Vegas is hurting right now and The Palms used to be the only place in town who would give me a free room for my stay. In this economy many hotels there now make the offer, and I'd stay at many of them over The Palms. That said, at an equal price (even if it was full price), I'd stay at many other hotels over The Palms. There is simply nothing that The Palms offers that justifies a room tag of $299+ on a weekend. I'm not coming back to stay at The Palms unless all the other offers dry up. I'll come for the sports bets and n9ne, but not for the hotel. The service/accommodations there just doesn't measure up to most other high end Las Vegas hotels.	
