Jun 21 2008 	Crossed my Palms with Silver	Imagine...you've worked hard for five months, sacrificed your social life to save for the road trip of a lifetime and you're starting this life changing Gran Turismo in the party capital of the world with your best friends you haven't seen for three years and now you have to choose a hotel. 'Holiday' or 'Vacation'- the name can be extremely misleadingly.After a few perfunctory phone calls to friends in the know, they recommended that we plan to reside in the Palms, being that it had been responsible for the majority of obscene celebrity party stories in the press for the past few months and (like everywhere in Vegas), there were no clocks, the slots paid out surprisingly well and the pool scene was disgustingly 'Vegas'. It sounded good to us.Following our ten hour flight, all I desired was for us to be whisked to our room in matter of minutes and that the lobby resounded with the chatter of a thousand slot machines to wake up my jet lagging mind. It didn't disappoint. There is a certain clean serenity to the lobby where so much debauchery allegedly takes place, but when the weary traveler is faced with this, alongside a smiling receptionist (with very funky nails) who upgrades you for free in a matter of minutes to a suite in the fantasy tower, you know you're in for a very smooth ride indeed.This place is just fun - good honest fun. It doesn't disguise itself with thematic restaurants, ridiculous decor and shouts its accolades at every conceivable moment - what the Palms delivers are good times handed to you sweetly and with a very broad smile. The staff know you're going to love it and you can tell. I have never been more charmed by smugness in my entire life, but then that's Vegas for you.The rooms you spend the least of your time in still beg for more of it, with humongous bath tubs, awesomely stocked mini-bars, luxurious white beds and wrap around windows that invite you to just languish on the floor with the lights off and be dazzled by the twinkling of a thousand neon lights at night. We did, I heartily recommend it.We ate in the heavens at Alize which had the view, but unfortunately lacked the opulence we hoped for as the service was particularly poor. Sum 41 were eating at a few tables down from us - so it might have been a slow night? The Ghostbar possesses a cinematic view of the strip, although the inside did lack in soul somewhat but then you just neck another Dirty Martini and forget about it whilst you laugh at how ridiculously OTT all of this is.The cabanas are well worth parting with your play money for as the service is excellent, so much so as I was given factor 50 sunblock by a Monolith of a security guard who was more interested in the well being of my skin than in throwing me out for an alcoholic misdemeanor. You wouldn't get this in good old Blighty I can tell you.Unfortunately, on account of my complete lack of sleep due to Virgin Atlantic and alcohol - we missed the Playboy Club, but were told in the morning that it was utterly everything you would expect from a club brandishing itself with a Playboy logo - I was gutted, but then I needed my strength for the 6 hour drive across Death valley and the desert to San Diego the next day.The morning we departed, we checked out easily with no surprises. We were very happy to pay handsomely for all the little extras we had, which has to tell you something about our stay. Broad smiles and laughter all round as we left, but not before breakfast. However, for some unknown reason, with everything else on offer being so good, the Palms kitchens can't cook eggs to order to save its life. Our companion sending hers back three times. Oh well, something had to give...	
