Jun 16 2008 	Nice	We went to Las Vegas in March 2008. We stayed 3 nights/4 days.Although sunny when we went, I'm glad we packed jeans and sweaters. The weather is unpridictable and can change day to day, it was cold the first 2 days we were there and by day 3 and 4 we were @ the pool.Let me say something about that pool. . . . WOW! It's really nice. The pool staff is extremley polite. You can choose to lounge on chairs, or pay for a cabana. We just used the lounge chairs provided and had a great time. We had a light lunch by the pool which was good but got a little expensive. Upon check-in we received 2 complimentary admissions to &quot;Ghost Bar&quot;. I beleive it's on the 55th floor. As with most places in Vegas ~ dress to impress! It was a nice upscale bar and the outside roof bar and patio area had great views of the strip and surrounding area. Our bar tab was out of hand though. Our own fault but 3 rounds of drinks for two ended up @ over $100 after tip. That was the only club we went to while staying there because Rain was closed. Moon was open one night but we were on the strip then and werent up for it after we got back.We spent very little time in our room (as expected). The bathroom was roomy. Could have been more storage space though. Our clothes bareley fit in the closet &amp; drawers provided. We ended up with a room with a double bed. We ended up sleeping in both of them (we dismissed housekeeping one day). The beds were very comfy! It was nice to have shades that kept out unwanted sunlight so we were able to sleep in. We tipped our housekeeping $20 for our entile stay. When they cleaned up they did a FAB job! We walked in on them once and they were so polite, asked how we were enjoying our stay and if there was anthing special we wanted them to do for our room. They kinda went above and beyond bc we were not the neatest guest while there. We were they to sleep and change quickley. The restraunts there were just ok. The 24/7 cafe was pretty good. The buffett was blah! We ate @ the buffet 3x. Once breakfast, and 2 lunches. There was a food court with Panda Express &amp; McDonalds. Best meal we had while in Vegas was actaully @ Margaritaville on the Strip-inexpensive and very tastey! The Casino part of the Hotel was a lot smaller than I thought it would be. But we just stuck with the $10 roulette (won some $$) and slots. For being a Maloof hotel (owners of the Sacramento Kings) we expected an out of this world sports bar. Nope. Just a circular bar with flat screens around. Bar staff was nice though.The Rio Hotel is across the street (kinda), we walked there. . . only took 5 mins. While there we went bowling @ Lucky Strike. Had a great time! Oh there is a movie theater @ the Palms also. Nice. After check out we had 5 hours to kill so we went and seen a movie! If you want a tattoo there is the Hart &amp; Hunintion Tattoo shop. Kinda neat to peek thru &amp; see whats going on. The Playboy store is pricey but fun to go into. The Palms store snacks, drinks and bathroom things you might have forgotten. Overall it was a nice Hotel with polite staff. I wouldn't say it was overpriced because everything in Vegas is expensive in general.	
Jun 13 2008 	My favorite hotel in Vegas.....	I used to live in Vegas a while ago and now my wife and I go back about 2-3 times a year and we ALWAYS try and stay at the Palms. I know locals dont really go out of their way to go to a Hotel/Casino in or around the strip but I would. The people at the hotel are nice, Ive eaten at all but 2 of the restaurants, and have been to all the clubs. The last time we went to Vegas we stayed at the Palms for 3 nights and we made up our minds that we were ONLY going to due stuff in the hotel (since we go all the time, we pretty much seen everything in vegas). Believe it or not, it was not that hard to do. The have a food court along with the fine dining, a movie theater, and a large sports book to watch all the games and such. We did leave the hotel only around midnight and walked across the street to Gold Coast becasue they have a $2.99 steak and eggs breakfast because most if not all of the places to eat at the Palms are closed by then. We have stayed in both towers and have stayed in regular rooms and we have stayed in a suite. Both were great just dont touch or pick up any of the Palms stuff in the room becasue you will be charged for it, it you dont believe me...try it. Yes all the clubs are cool and they are expensive to drink in but just drink for free in the casino before you go up. I will stay there as many times as I can as long as its open. Peace out from Dallas.	
Jun 8 2008 	Great stay at the Palms will return!	Just returned from a 4 night golf trip to Vegas in which we stayed at the Palms. We were 4 guys from Vancouver ranging in age from 34 to 43. We arrived at the hotel on Monday at about 1pm hoping to check in to our two rooms. Only one room was ready, which was not a big deal since we just wanted to drop off our bags before heading to the course. But by the time we got back from the car, the desk clerk saw us and informed us that the second room was also ready. Our rooms were in the original tower and they were a bit on the smaller side, but they were clean and the beds were really comfortable. The bathrooms were actually quite large. The casino itself is also on the smaller side compared to the other much bigger casinos. However, our group actually found this to be a plus since we could all go off and do our own thing and not have to really look to find each other. Since we were there during the week, we never had a problem finding a table to play blackjack on. It became noticeably busier on Thursday with the weekend crowd arriving. The pool was great. No problem getting lounge chairs in the mid afternoon. The pool has a large center bar and a you can order food to be delivered to your spot. The pool has a lively atmosphere and but was relaxing at the same time. Also this was our first midweek trip to Vegas and we were quite surprised to find that the girl to guy ratio is about 7 to 1 from Monday to Wednesday at the pool. It was a very pleasant surprise. By Thursday afteroon the ratio shifted to about 60/40 guys to girls.The Palms has 4 separate nightclubs on the premises. We went to two of them and had a great time It's a lively fun hotel, slanted towards a younger crowd. But by no means was it all just young people. Also it not being on the strip was actually a plus for us since we had a car for golf and the hotel had easy highway access. We booked 3 nights and got the 4th night free and found the Palms to be way beyond what we expected for the price we paid. We were all very happy with our stay and the Palms and are already planning our return trip there next year!!	
