Feb 28 2008 	Overrated - Stay away	After over 50 visits to Las Vegas hotels for business and pleasure in my life, I'd have to say that the Palms is the most overrated hotel I've ever experienced. I have stayed there 4 times and each time gets worse. This last time, we arrived for a conference and looking forward to a brief rest before heading out for a meeting. The front desk informed us that they had given away our prepaid room because we arrived there late. After a lengthy but futile conversation with the front desk clerk, we were referred to the assistant manager which led to an even more frustrating discussion about how they are legally allowed to give away rooms even if the rooms were fully prepaid. Luckily, we found availability at the Bellagio so we left. Stay away from this hotel unless you want to be treated like a number on their spreadsheet. The Palms is also geared towards a younger but shadier crowd.	
Feb 27 2008 	Palms Playboy Palace	The Palms resort is great for people in their early twenties to mid thirties. The rooftop club is mind-boggling, and the Playboy Club is pretty cool too. The pool-scene is nice, casino is small and the hotel is pretty far off the strip. We walked across the street to some HillBilly hotel to catch the shuttle to the strip as this was free as opposed to taking a taxi to and from the strip every day. The pizza and italian food in this hotel is horrible and over priced. The beds are really comfy and the rooms and bathrooms are kept really clean. I had a great time and slept well when needed. One more thing, regardless what building you are in, the higher up you stay, the more you will hear the bass thumping at night from the nightclub on the roof of the playboy tower. Keep that in mind especially if you go to bed early or have kids.	
Feb 10 2008 	This was a let down	This hotel is all hype. I would have left early but booked through travelworm and they were not going to refund my $$ if I checked out into another hotel. I don't like paying for simple services that are generally free in most hotels. $13 a day for internet and $25 for the gym is a little annoying. All the clubs and bars were decent. As a hotel guest you can get into the Ghostbar for free except on fridays and saturdays. The others charge between $20 to $40 to get in. The french restaurant Alize on the top floor was awesome, but extremely expensive. Great view of the city at night and very romantic. I will probably never stay here again. There are better hotels on the strip and if you like the nightlife here then just cab it!	
Jan 29 2008 	Stayed there with small children...	and had a great time. I was a bit concerned about going to a hotel with such a &quot;party&quot; rep with two small kids, but it was never a problem.We had booked the lowest tier room through an online discount site but were automatically upgraded to the Fantasy Tower. The gentleman at the desk said we'd be more comfortable with the kids in those rooms. The queen beds were very comfortable and the bathroom was huge. The room was also remarkably quiet - we heard no noise for the three nights we were there. The kids went to Kids Quest, a childcare facility right off the casino floor, for an hour each day while mommy and daddy gambled. The staff was extremely nice and we felt very safe with our kids there. The kids had a ball playing video games and ordering up slushies at the kiddie bar. We had a rental car, so the rest of our trip was spent out and about (there are lots of things to do with kids in vegas - hiking at Red Rocks, the children's museum, pinball hall of fame, chocolate factory). Whenever we came back to The Palms, it was only a short, easy walk to the room. The casino isn't horribly smoky during the day and shady characters were few and far between. At night the crowd does get younger and rowdier, but we were upstairs asleep by then. The closest we came to party animals was early Sunday morning - as I was exiting the elevator with my kids to go to breakfast a group of 20somethings were just coming in from a hard night out. Everyone involved found it amusing. A downside: The buffet was &quot;meh&quot; at best. We did a dinner and a breakfast there and were unimpressed. It's not worth it. Go to Luxor for breakfast or Red Rocks Resort (which has a great Kids Quest facility) or Spice Market at Planet Hollywood for dinner.	
Jan 27 2008 	Fun Party Hotel	I went to Vegas with my best friends to celebrate our 21st birthdays (b/c we're all born within the same 2 weeks.) We decided to stay at the Palms because we heard it was a great hotel for younger people. We heard right. There were lots of people in their 20s. The rooms were nice. We stayed in the old tower. The only problem was that there was not that much light in the room, so we couldn't see as well when putting on make up. The light in the bathroom was sufficient though.We had breakfast at the hotel every day. The food is great at the 24 hour café and it’s very reasonably priced. We went to Little Buddha one night. The food was great. Also, my friend described the steak at N9NE as the best she ever had! We didn't go to any of the clubs or lounges in the hotel itself, but we did get passes for free admission because we were staying in the hotel. The pool was nice, but it closes early, at 6pm. It’s not even sundown at that time yet :-( The pool also wasn't very deep, maybe 4 feet at most. There were red floaties for the pool and also floating tables with umbrellas. There was a great crowd by the pool. We had to wake up very early to reserve spots by the pool though. There are chairs that are reserved that you have to pay for, and lots of times, they were just empty b/c no one was paying for them. There are also cabanas you can rent for a day. One of the nights, there was a private party so they closed the pool early. But I guess that’s the price we had to pay for staying at such a popular party hotel.Overall, we had a great time at the hotel and when I go back to Vegas, I will definitely stay at the Palms again!	
Jan 24 2008 	A good experience	Normally running around $320 per night, I found an online deal to stay at the Palms for only $55 per night. When we arrived, our room wasn't ready and we were promptly upgraded to the new Fantasy Tower. These rooms were luxurious and very nice-- running close to $400 per night. The hotel staff was very accomodating. The only problem is that this hotel is very far from the strip and is unwalkable. The hotel offers shuttles every 2 hours, but it is all luck whether or not you will catch one. A cab ride to Caesar's will cost you $10-$15 which can get quite costly. Besides nightclubs, a casino and a few restaurants, there is not much to do here . . . there is virtually no stores or attractions like many of the other hotels on the strip. Stay here if you plan to spend a majority of your time in the nightclubs (Palms has 4) or away from the action of the strip.	
