Jul 20 2007 	Palms made the Perfect long weekend!!	A group of 11 girls (23-24) stayed at The Palms for Memorial Day Weekend and had the time of our lives! The Palms is the perfect place for a group of friends who want to have a good time. We squeezed in 5 and 6 girls per Suite with no problem at all - just don't tell the hotel that you plan on having more than 2 people stay per room or they will charge you an additional $30 per person per night. Sharing 4 keys between 11 people was annoying, but totally worth the savings. We contacted the Palms directly to get a special rate and also to ensure that we didn't have to wait at any of the lines at their clubs (Playboy Lounge, Moon, Rain, GhostBar).Friday - we ate at Nove which was pretty good Italian food, pretty expensive (but that's everywhere in Vegas). However, the benefit of eating here was that you could take a side entrance into Playboy Lounge and Moon (without dealing with lines of people). Originially they wanted $60 cover per person, but we simply asked if we could get in for free (since it was 11 cute girls) and they let us in for free, gave us VIP wristbands (saw John O'Hurley from Seinfeld), gave us all the Ketel One vodka we wanted, and were able to sit at a table without paying for bottle service. It was pretty amazing. They also let us into Moon for free - I recomend getting one of the Tables that is out on the balcony - it overlooks the entire Strip (very beautiful).The pool at the Palms on Saturday was pretty low-key and we went to Tao at the Venitian for dinner (AMAZING Asian food) - I reccomend it to everyone!On Sunday, we went to The Palms Pool and got out there pretty early (9am), which was an excellent idea because they had a &quot;pool party&quot; and it got packed very quickly. non-guests had to pay $45 to get in...We had a blast and would reccomend it to anyone wanting to get a tan and have some drinks and listen to loud party music with a huge amount of people. It wasn't as &quot;spring-breaky&quot; as it could've been; I feel like it was a lot of people 21 and older. There weren't any raunchy contests or people with no tops on.Half of our group went to see Cirque D' Solei &quot;O&quot; at the Belagio, which was pretty amazing but I don't think it was worth the $100 ticket.FYI: If you plan on going to the Strip and walking around to the different casinos wear COMFORTABLE shoes. It felt like a mile walk just walking from the Belagio to Ceasar's. We did take a break at Wild Bill's Casino because they had cheap beer (and we needed to rest our feet!)We were planning on going to Pure nightclub in Ceasar's Palace on Saturday night, but the line was insane (an hour wait at least).In conclusion, the Palms staff made us feel like VIPs in their hotel and we had an AMAZING time that we are still talking about to this day. The Palms is perfect for a bachelorette or bachelor party (we met at least 6 different groups of bachelor parties). It's also perfect for a group of guys or girls from 21 to 29 who want to have a good time. NOTE (especially for guys): be prepared to spend a LOT of money - nothing is cheap, unless someone else is paying for your drinks...	
Jul 19 2007 	If you fit the target audience - it's great	After using trip advisor numerous times, I wanted to contribute, so please bare with my first review.I stayed at the Palms in Las Vegas for 6 nights spanning June/July 2007. It was my first trip to Vegas, and I had read up quite a bit. I'm 27, and was quite frankly, looking to party and enjoy myself. I was interested in being around similar minded people. In that regard, The Palms was perfect. The rates on the weekend during the summer are pretty exhorbitant - $300 - $400 a night. Weekday rates were much more reasonable low to mid $100's. Overall, I averaged about $200 a night plus 9% tax. I certainly could have found cheaper, and I've no interest in throwing money away, but I felt I got value. What exceeded my expectation?* The room, though pretty basic amenity wise, was close to perfect. It was spotless and obviously either new or newly renovated. I run a lodging business myself, so I undertand the cycle of a room from new to the time it needs renovation, so while I give credit to the room for being in excellent condtion, it was basically new.* The nightlife at Palms. I expected it to be fun, but now there are three popular nightclubs in the resort itself. The new Moon clubs is very chic. The older Rain I guess is losing it's status to other clubs. I didn't go there, but saw a long line to get in, so it can't be completely washed up. Ghost Bar is a cool smaller venue, and also had quite a line. With lines to three clubs in a fairly small central area by Vegas Standards (this certainly isn't like MGM, Mirage, etc.), you really feel you are in the middle of something pretty much from 10 p.m. to about 5 a.m.* The guests at Palms. I already mentioned my age and desire to be around like minded people. * The Pool scene. This was a lot of fun. I went To the party on Friday and had a blast all day. Saturday, though not a party was almost as crowded and as much fun. It got a lot slower during the week - no surprise I guess. You had to be a guest to use the pool, except on Friday, which you a non-guest could buy their way in for $30 I think. I met quite a few people on non-party days who weren't staying at the hotel, but instead across the street at cheaper places like Orleans and Rio. Supposedly, a bribe to the guy at the door gets you in without a problem. The only thing I REALLY DIDN&quot;T LIKE at the pool was that if you left your chair for a while, they would give it to somebody else, even if you left some belongings there. Nothing like walking to the bar and coming back to find a stranger in chair. *Food court - Don't ask me why, but I was for some reason thrilled that there was a small food court with McDonalds, Sbarro, and some quick Chinese place. Sometimes, you just don't want to spend $20 eating a few bites from the buffet. What pretty much met expectations:* Restaurants, staff, overall cleanliness, etc. I'm not a gambler, but if I were, I probably would have been dissapointed by the size of the casino. It is a fraction of the size of others. Palms really is more about the party than the gambling. * Concierge got me tickets to see KA. Though I find it funny that she just ordered them off of the Vegas.com website. (Super, Great, Fantastic, Wonderful, show by the way) What missed expectations:* There was a kind of horrible noise coming from the bathroom. It's just a plumbing issue, but something nobody seemed interested in fixing.* Getting charged $5 for somebody to bring a package to my room. I certainly could have picked it u myself when I walked by the business center every few hours. It's a small amount, but felt as though I was purposely not told about fee. It's more the principle than the pain. * Getting dinged for a small bottle of wine I never had out of The mini-bar. Later, I realized it was because I took the bottle opener and must have done something to register on their computer system. * The promoted free shuttle to the Strip is pretty much worthless. It comes every 2 hours for about 10 hours out of the day and only drops you off at two malls (Fashion and Ceasers). The driver told me that they used to run non-stop, but usually just ran around empty, so they cut back. It's a $8 - $12 taxi ride. It seems to me that an intelligent hotel manager would make arrangements with the Rio and/or Orleans for a joint shuttle if they aren't busy enough. * $10 a night internet. I know I shouldn't complain about this, as it's becoming more and more common, and some hotels charge much higher prices, but sheesh... A high speed commercial internet connection to the hotel costs what.. $200 a month? A few pieces of $50 equipment? And 1000+ rooms? can't you just offer one small complimentary service that will make me feel good? You can even force a bunch of promotions to my computer screen - I won't mind. * Pepsi machine on floor. First, they would not Except bills under any circumstance, despite having the part to do this. Trying different floors to find a machine that would take bills (I never did find one), I learned that some floors have $3 Diet Pepsis and other floors have $2 Diet Pepsis. They tried to get me, but I outsmarted them. Take that Maloof brothers. So as you can see, the Palms nailed all the important stuff, and my complaints are pretty petty. I would love to stay there again. Actually, I'm going back to Vegas in August and tried to book again, but they bumped their rates to $550 a night on the weekend. Hopefully Hardrock will be as much fun at 1/2 the price.	
