May 5 2007 	Love the Palms I pratically live here...	The Palms is without a doubt my favorite hotel in Las Vegas (I'm a local). There's plenty to do (spa, movie theatre, AWESOME concert venue, not to mention FOUR club venues) and I love this place. The food is great, there's something for every price range. The rooms in the Fantasy Tower are beautiful. I stayed here in December for my 21st birthday celebration and I was NOT disappointed. I'm planning on spending my 22nd birthday here too!!!Beware, some of the security guards are totally power tripping (mainly the ones in the club and outside the towers checking for keys). The front desk staff is wonderful! If you want a great rate, try checking the online wholesalers; especially this summer. A lot of the websites are doing buy one night get the second night free promotions for week nights. I booked one online for $107 on the first night with the second night free!If you have small children, this might not be the best place to stay. There are activities for them (small arcade, movie theatre, childcare facility), but if you are trying to keep from exposing them to the 21 and up Vegas crowd, this is not the place. Most of the hotel caters to the senior citizen crowd during the day and the 21 and up crowd at night. If you don't fit one of those groups, you might be uncomfortable. Otherwise, it's a great time!	
Apr 18 2007 	Better than expected	Just got back from a 1 night stay at the Palms. I booked a stay in a superior room in the Fantasy Tower. Upon arrival I was upgraded to a premier corner room without even asking. The room was better than I anticipated. Large King bed, large flat screen TV and &quot;hip&quot; modern decor. Room was very spacious and probably more than I needed since I was traveling alone. View was great with two corner windows facing the strip; although be warned that the strip is probably a mile away if you intend to walk to it. My only complaint is the bathroom. Don't get me wrong, it is large and well appointed, but as a previous reviewer commented, the sink is an engineering disaster. It is impossible to wash your hands or even rinse you toothbrush without pouring water all over the granite countertop. I almost electricuted myself when I left the blowdryer plugged in sitting on the countertop as I tried to wash my face and noticed the water flowing all over the top surface.Besides this flaw in design, the room and service were very good. I would certainly stay there again.	
Apr 13 2007 	maybe a bit too cool for school	I was in Vegas on business with my girlfriend tagging along, and my company booked us at the Palms. I had heard about how youthful and trendy it had become, so I was curious. I'm 42, so not quite into the twenty-something scene anymore, but thought it would be a nice break from the depressing scene at most other casino hotels.It was definately hip and happening, but often annoyingly so. The areas around the fantasy tower felt like a meat-market neon-night club, with maybe a few too many twenty-somethings dressed all alike (guys: fashionable blue jeans, leather shoes, button up long-sleeve shirt with cuffs rolled back one fold, killer looking wrist watch, tassled/spiked hair. Girls: high heels, mini skirts and tiny dresses, tiny purses, hair ironed flat) and trying to see and been seen.There were bouncer-like guards posted at the base of the Fantasy tower, checking to see if people had room keys. This was reassuring, but it also added to the whole grease-ball-night-club-bouncer feel. I kept joking with my girlfriend that I was going to be denied access to our room because I wasn't wearing trendy clothes. We made great sport counting the number of guys we saw stalking about in the same style of trendy threads and hairdos. At one point we counted six before we could get 15 yards from the front desk.I had a room in the fantasy tower, and the room was wonderful. The LCD wide screen TV was nice when it worked (the digital channels tended to freeze up a lot), and the jacuzi tub was fantastic. The bed was comfortable. My girlfriend and I could not get the wireless keyboard/internet to work. The lighting around the entertainment center was sorely lacking, making it hard to see anything there. Bring a flashlight.I was thrilled at the assortment of soaps, toothpaste, shaver and other goodies there for you. It came in handy since we forgot some things -- saved us a walk through the meat-market to go get these things from the front desk.Food at the Palms' 24/7 cafe was so-so. For some reason it took a long time to get seated, even though there were easily a half dozen tables vacant. Weird... (is it trendy to make people wait nowadays?) and a snooty waiter made the experience even less memorable. We ended up finding a hugely better meal across the street at the otherwise boring Gold Coast Casino. There is a fantastic Dim Sum Chinese restaurant inside. Well worth the wait to get into that joint. (we do dim sum in Chinatown, Los Angeles and this was as good).Would we go back to the Palms? Probably not.	
Apr 11 2007 	Room = great overall = just ok	We stayed at The Palms for a friends' 40th birthday. The stay was just ok, with the exception of the room. Upon arriving, we waited at the front desk with no other travelers to check-in and waited, and waited, and waited. Finally, the girl said, &quot;Oh, I'm sorry. Are you waiting to check-in?&quot; Whatever, like she didn't see us. Anyway, she was kind enough to upgrade us to the Fantasy Tower and a beautiful suite. The room was clean and huge with three plasma tv's, separate living room, and bathroom with jacuzzi tub and the third plasma. It was indeed a very nice room with an awesome view which totally made our stay.Regarding our stay, the casino and restaurants in the hotel were quite boring. Not many people there. No real draw factor. There was a UFC fight scheduled for that week so the majority of the folks we saw were young and covered with tattoos. Not our crowd. The pool was open and non-eventful. Women walked around in small bikini's which I totally approve of, but walking around in 4 inch heels?????? Come on. There was drinking ongoing at the pool which is fine, but not when beer cans are being tossed around the pool and left there. We got a sandwich from the Vegas Sandwich Shop which was very good and not pricey, but I had to wait 20 minutes for it. It's a counter service sandwich shop, not a sit-down and several other people were just as angry as myself.The Playboy Club / Moon club is located in the hotel and saw some nice sites entering and leaving, but I'm not paying $40 for cover. Then again, you're in Vegas. Everything associated with &quot;partying&quot; is expensive.They have shuttles at a price to take you to the strip or airport, but found a cab was actually cheaper. They also have a movie theater located in the hotel / casino, but I just couldn't go since I could see a movie anytime at home. But I was quite tempted as there was nothing really to do at the PalmsWould I stay there again....probably not. Too far from the strip to actually enjoy Vegas and not enough to make me stay at the Palms.	
