Mar 23 2007 	Pleasant stay at the Palms	My boyfriend &amp; I decided on the Palms for a 3-night, 2-day stay in Vegas in March. The rates were reasonable and we liked the reputation for attracting a young crowd. We had no problems upon check-in except receiving a room with 2 beds instead of the 1 king that we had requested. The woman at the front desk was polite and told us to check in the next day around noon, and we did move to a room with a king bed the next day promptly at noon with no issues.Our first room was 8-117, which overlooked the front drive of the casino and Flamingo Road. The room was spacious, the bathroom amenities were nice, and the beds were comfortable, though maybe not deserving of their &quot;Most Comfortable Bed in Vegas&quot; title. There are a lot of pillows, a thick comforter and two sheets. I found it a little excessive personally but wasn't bothered by it.Our second room, 30-112, overlooked the Fantasy Tower and the pool. It was also clean and exactly as described. Our one gripe with the rooms was that the air conditioning cools the area directly in front of it but really does nothing to cool the rest of the room. As it was March, this was not a major problem, but during the summer months it may be more of a hassle.As for the rest of the property, we ate at the 24/7 Cafe 3 times, twice for breakfast and once for a snack after dinner. The staff in the mornings was a bit surly and service was slow - a couple eventually stormed out on our 2nd morning there. In the morning, it was a completely different atmosphere - the waitstaff was pleasant and hurrying to help everyone. We also ate at the Panda Express in the food court once. It was overpriced but quick - something that can't be said about the makeshift buffet that is open until the new Fantasy Buffet is done. We waited in line for the buffet for 10 minutes while tables were open before leaving.We are not big gamblers but did use some of the slot and video poker machines and had no complaints. The Palms' casino floor doesn't have the dark, depressing atmosphere as some of the other casinos and is comparatively quiet. We also sat out by the pool one afternoon and really enjoyed the atmosphere and design of the area.My only hesitation about the Palms is its distance from the Strip. We spent $10 on a one-way trip to the Strip each time. There are always cabs waiting in the front drive, so it is no problem, but the time and money adds up. If you don't want to see any of the other hotels and want to take advantage of the Palms' restaurants, clubs, and quiet casino floor, by all means, stay here, but if you are a first-timer like we were, I would recommend staying on the Strip and saving the Palms until you are a Vegas veteran.	
