Jan 20 2007 	Great Nightclubs..Watch for the elevators	I stayed at the Palms resort on business from January 14-17 2008. The rooms are very nice with oversized pillows and down comforters. The nightclubs were the best part about the casino. The lounges had nice lighting and a cool atmosphere. The casino itself was VERY smokey. If you are non-smoker you will feel like you smoked a pack of cigarettes every morning when you wake up.A group of us got stuck in the elevator going up the Fantasy Tower. The hotel handled this in a horrible fashion. We had to call the fire department to help us. We were stuck for over an hour without air. Bring your cell phones with you in the elevator in case you have this problem. Apparently, the elevators are weight sensitive. This was the third &quot;elevator mishap&quot; in two days. The Palms is off the strip so you will need to take about a $10.00 cab ride to the strip. Overall, I would stay at the Palms again.	
Jan 19 2007 	Palms is a must... and affordable on weekdays	Booked a room on Travelocity the day before and got the same rate as at the Palms website. The Palms was one of the best hotels I've stayed at in Vegas, though I have to admit I usually prefer a cheap room to save money. Here are the highlights:* Easy access- it's right off the freeway at the Flamingo exit. There's a ton of daytime traffic, but no foot traffic so the left turn to the valet was easy. Check-in was smooth (3pm Monday) and the easily accessed elevators (Fantasy Tower) had a security guy who made sure only guests could go up.* Room!- The second you walk in you know you're at the Palms that everyone raves about. The room was very up-to-date, with nice linens and duvet, flat screen tv, Bose wave radio alarm clock by the bed (thinking about buying one now!), desk next to the window, bath that was huge, with marble counter, whirlpool bath/shower and the shower head was the highest I've ever seen. Usually I have to stooop to take a shower but this one was up there at over 6 feet and had great pressure. Comfy towels, close up swing away mirror and lots of goodies like body scrub, special shampoos and lotions, even a new razor and toothpaste! And this was the lowest priced room they have!* Food- went to the Italian restaurant which was expensive (steaks started at $44) but it is way up at the top (53rd floor) with a great view. They have an extensive Italian wine list. The 24/7 Cafe next to the casino had reasonably priced food, good quality, fast service and multiple big screen plasmas to watch if you're alone!*Clubs- The Playboy Club was awesome despite the $20 cover but most people were going to Ghostbar and guests get in free. They have a separate elevator and access is really controlled. The club is small, with a bar running most of one side. Lots of RESERVED signs on tables, so you might need reservations. The view out on the big pation was incredible. It's on the 55th floor and there's a plexiglass window in the floor that (if you have the guts) you can walk on! It was freezing out there (29 degrees) during this extra cold weather and they had no heat lamps. Come late March it should be more comfortable.Other things I can tell you is that there is a parking garage just off the east side of the hotel- make a left at the light before you get to the Palms- and it is close to the casino and the elevator. The slot machines weren't too loose, though I won on the huge Wheel of Fortune machine. The pool area is currently closed but looked awesome.The room has a well stocked bar but since the prices are outrageous don't touch anything, because when you remove a bottle you get electronically charged for it instantly! Then you have to explain why you didn't want it!	
