Oct 16 2006 	Great stay...we'll definitely be back...	My wife and I took a couple days during the week to head to Vegas for our 11th anniversary. My wife is a celeb nut, so I figured our best bet would be the Palms...We arrived in Vegas via car...an easy 3.5 hour drive from our home in North Phoenix. Dropped the car with valet...the hey-boys from the bell stand promptly took our bags and we were off to check-in.The only hiccup in our stay was at check-in, but it ended up being just fine...better than fine. We had reserved a king, non-smoking room...just a regular room. They didn't have any available. They had a non-smoking room with 2 double beds...umm, it our anniversary, doubles ain't gonna cut it. Or they had a smoking room with 2 queen beds. Better but not ideal...So my wife, who is an expert at subtlely working people and getting what she wants, went to work on the girl behind the counter. By the time we left check-in, the manager in charge of the check-in area had released a grand suite to us...all for the low, low price of $129 a night.The room was great...great view, great lighting, comfortable furniture, great flat screen TVs with Bose surround, cool bar, great shower with jets everywhere. My wife was in heaven with the tub...big enough for 2, it had jacuzzi jets everywhere and filled from a hole in the ceiling...too cool.Night #1...We ate at Gardunos the first night since we just wanted some light fare...the mixed dips and rolled tacos were amazing. Then we headed upstairs to the ghostbar. Kind of a disappointment...some convention was at the hotel and you had a room full of 50-year-olds wearing shiny tinsel wigs or giant foam cowboy hats and glow stick hanging from their necks or glow stick belts. And the staff at the door was breaking their own rules of not letting groups of guys larger than 4 into the bar. We were hoping for a more even mix of folks and a younger, slightly less glow stick wearing crowd. We left and hit the slots...Night #2...We ate at N9NE...the steakhouse and had an awesome dinner. My wife had the parmesan crusted lamb chops and I had the filet mignon of course. We also ordered the crispy fries, which were way too crispy and came in a pile so big it looked like a tumbleweed. How many potatoes had to die for that nest to be made...We split a bottle of Martinelli Pinot Noir...definitely worth the price, no matter the price. We then decided to give ghostbar one more shot. Much better the second time around. All the conventioneers were gone and the crowd was roughly 50-50 male-female.Will we be back? Absolutely! We wont be staying anywhere else in Vegas.Other Vegas hotels we've stayed at for comparison...Las Vegas HiltonRitz-CarltonFour SeasonsLuxorAladdinFlamingo	
