Sep 13 2006 	Good overall review but lacked something....	We recently returned from a 5 day stay at the Palms. We were out for a bachelor party with about 12 guys. This group is more of the corporate america group, not the wild and crazy strippers and getting arrested group.Front Desk:I forget her name but she was great. Upgraded our standard rooms to a Playboy Tower room and a Junior Suite. The others in the party were also mostly upgraded as well. Check-in was quick as could be.Pool:Best part of the hotel, period. They did a great job renovating the pool area. Friday is their big pool party and it was a great one. Not TOO crowded like the Rehab party is at the Hard Rock, but crowded enough with a good atmosphere.Our waitress Alice, was very good and attentive. We rented a cabana on Friday and got one of the Caves. So worth it with a big group like that, although I cant see the value other days.Atmosphere:Kind of dead. I definately expected more out of the Palms. The casino was never crowded, even on the weekends. The center bar was pretty lame. It just lacked the life of the Hard Rock.Restaurants:N9NE - We had a big party (18). They were supposed to set for 17 but only set for 15 so we were crowded. They didnt do much in terms of accomadating us.The food was very very good, but I have eaten at better steakhouses in Vegas (Charlie Palmer). The steak was rare when we were told medium rare-medium. It was even tough to cut it was so rare. Maybe it had to do with the large party but I would guess 16 of us ordered the Rib Eye. Appetizers and sides were amazing.Little Buddah - My favorite Restaurant on the whole trip. What a gem this place is. Everything was great; atmosphere, food, service...all top notch. We all mostly ate sushi except for some hot appetizers. Everything was great. Cant wait to go to the Buddah Bar in NYC, its sister restaurant.Diner - Okay, at best. Service was SLOW. Strange in Vegas. Wood was okay. Fine if you're just grabbing some eggs in the morning.Food Court - Ben and Jerry's Phish Food Shakes - YUMMMMM.Spa:I only used the gym and ammenities but everything was clean and in good working order. Anyone I know who went for a message loved it.Rooms:We had a room in the Playboy tower. Well designed and clean. Nothing to complain about. We couldnt figure out how to turn on the jets in the jaccuzzi bath though I dont think anyone would have really used it. The speaker in the bathroom was a nice touch.Nightlife:Typical Vegas stuff. I swear all these clubs are run by the same person. Same scene, same type of music. I hate hip-hop and thats all I heard. Ghost Bar was all hip-hop all the time and one big sausage fest. Rain was a cool looking club but the music just got to me after a while. Please play some house music. I wear pants that fit.I dont think I am forgetting anything else. I enjoyed my stay there but if given the choice would go back to the Hard Rock before the Palms. Sunday night at the Hard Rock was jumping when we left at around 1. The Palms was absolutely dead when we walked in.Celebrity Sightings...Lance Bass at the pool party. Sug Knight in the casino. Tim Duncan playing blackjack at a $15 table. A BUNCH of basketball players I didnt know.	
Sep 6 2006 	Had a great time	My husband and I went to celebrate his 32nd birthday. We picked this hotel because we have heard good things about the hotel as far as the great bars and pool. Our sole intention was to have a fabulous time. We pulled into the valet and I was immediately impressed. The valet not only rushed over to open my door but also offered his hand to help me out. He then assisted my husband with the luggage and asked if we needed bell service. I'm sure this sounds pretty standard but this is the first time I have pulled into a valet and wasn't immediately scribbled a claim check before the valet was off to the next car. My husband and I got to the resverations desk (we stayed during the week and booked our room at a rate of $95). My husband asked if there were any complimentary upgrades available and Harvey (the reservations clerk) told us not to worry he had already fixed us up with a nice room. Again, we were pleasantly surprised with the great service and headed to our room. Harvey had put us up in a grand duluxe suite that was apprx 1,000sq ft with 2 bathrooms living room and huge master bedroom with jacuzzi tube. By far the best thing about this room was the bed -- it was simply a piece of heaven!! I am not particularly a picky sleeper, I dont have any back problems and can pretty much sleep comfortably anywhere, so to have this bed catch my attention is definitely noteworthy! I absolutely loved this bed and hated having to leave it.As far as the casino goes -- it is a smaller casino, which can be both a good thing and a bad thing. Though it is smaller it still maintains all of the excitement and energy that any larger casino would hold. The casino hosted a welcoming ambiance and staff was always friendly and helpful. We did some gambling here, but we always venture out to different casinos so the size did not really bother us. Tables here were a little on the high end ($15 and up for craps) and we did not find our favorite slot machines here, but there were plenty others to choose from. Our only complaint was the waitressing service. We waited about 40min for our first drinks. I believe the cause of this was a convention in a nearby banquet room which diverted all of it's waitresses to serving the needs of these people. We were slightly annoyed.For the evenng of my husband's birthday we celebrated at the ghost bar. The view is magnificent and breathtaking. Get there early so you can stake out a seat before they are all gone. Free seatng is limited. They do, however, have tables that can be reserved for people purchasing bottle service which is well into the hundreds (a little pricey for the average). We also managed to join a pool party one night, which was also a lot of fun. Lots of cozy cabanas for couples to relax in. We found one and watched the live band and did some people watching and took in the whole experience from the comfort of our little cabana!Overall, our stay was pleasant. We were very satisfied with the service. The &quot;complimentary&quot; upgrade exceeded our expectations and proves that the hotel cares about it's guests . We will definitely stay again.	
Aug 27 2006 	I loved this place!	I really enjoyed my stay here. A lot of the reviews here seem to center on the &quot;personality&quot; of the hotel staff. I didn't encounter any issues with that. To the contrary, I received a warm welcome at check-in, and at valet was surprised to be greeted by name when I came back to the hotel in the afternoon. The only &quot;grumps&quot; I encountered were the guys checking the room keys at the elevator. They never smiled, but I think that's a &quot;I'm a tough bouncer&quot; kind of thing, it just cracked me up every time I saw them, like trying to make the guards at Buckingham Palace laugh or something...The room was nice. Very comfortable bed, nice bathroom, nice TV. I did not encounter any &quot;neighbor noise&quot; even though they mentioned the hotel was sold out for my stay. The only negative is that the air conditioning didn't seem cool enough for me in late afternoon, although later at night it was ok. Maybe the sun coming through the sheer curtains all day heated the room up.Nice casino, I'm a video poker fan and they had a good selection. I had no problem getting drink service, it was frequent enough for me. One time the waitress had gone off somewhere, just hitting the change light on the machine brought a slot person around and they sent over the waitress right away.I didn't eat at the property much, so I have little to comment on. I like the fact that you can grab a quick and inexpensive bite at the food court. Vegas Subs is there and they are one of my favorites in town. And my one meal at the breakfast buffet was only &quot;ok&quot;, nothing to rave about. But at $6 it's one of the cheaper options in town. I'll definitely be back at the Palms.	
