Jan 23 2006	Warning:Wicked Witch of the Desk!	I felt compelled to finally write about my Palms experience as I owe it to my fellow travelers, who have helped me tremendously in choosing pleasant accomodations!...Upon check-in for a 2 night stay, the front desk clerk, Marci, greeted us coldly and annoyed with the ever so welcoming &quot;Last name?&quot;. Extremely hostile, she punched at the keys on her keyboard, it was obvious she was agitated to have to 'deal' with yet another pestering guest. I asked her for a price adjustment as rates had become less expensive since I booked w/ travelocity. &quot;No, there's nothing I can do for you&quot;, she barked. After a few minutes of unneccesary debate she revealed that the only way it could be resolved was through my 'outside' booking source. Not a great first impression but nonetheless, we kept a positive attitude, we were there to relax and enjoy, right?! Our bell man assisted us w/ our bags and was great: very helpful, efficient and COURTEOUS! We had paid for an upgrade to jacuzzi suite at the front desk and soon came to find that Marci had chosen a suite w/ a view(we had requested a nice view)of the building power generator on a floor just beneath noisy drilling/construction. Still we decided to make the most of it...my fiance went downstairs to order champagne for us at the bar. After five minutes of watching the bartender acknowledge everything but him, he was finally greeted with a head nod. He ordered bubbly and seeing as the bar had no other guests, tipped very generously to make up for the lack of business. He did not receive so much as a simple thanks. It was beginning to feel that perhaps we weren't exactly welcomed at the Palms. Long story short: Upon check-out, we decided to try our luck with Marci again. It turns out our prior experience was not a circumstance of her just &quot;having a bad day&quot;. Greeted AGAIN angrily by &quot;Last name?!&quot;, not a 'how was your stay' or 'how may I help you?' She totalled up our bill to an outrageous total. It turns out she charged us for nearly the entire refridgerator worth of spirits and mixers although we consumed nothing! We proceeded to tell her we had used it for our leftovers from dinner one night but did not use one item and asked why we were still charged. Infuriated, she scolded us, &quot;it's a mini-bar NOT A FRIDGE, I have to charge you.&quot; I was stunned! We argued until reluctantly, she told us &quot;half off is as good as I can do&quot;. I was furious! Finally, she said she would send someone up to our room to make sure we hadn't consumed anything, and it would be figured out by the time we returned to get our bags(which were kindly held by the bell desk for a few hours). Upon returning to the front desk, we inquired about our bill with a different clerk, who informed us that not a thing was done to reverse a single charge. We were shocked and felt terribly mistreated! The new clerk apologized and said it was no problem to reverse all the charges...we could'nt believe how easy it was resolved after all this turmoil Marci put us through! Overall, the negatives strongly outweighed the positives (bell desk and the comfy beds)with this hotel. We could not wait to get home so we could finally relax and try to recover from our nightmare experience w/ Marci! For all the publicity this hotel gets, we were FAR from impressed! I worked in the hotel industry for five years, am extremely understanding and rarely complain. This was the worst customer service I have EVER received.	
Jan 7 2006	Almost perfect	I had a 1,000 sq. ft. suite on the 53rd floor( I was upgraded; my lifestyle is much closer to Timex than Rolex) with drop-dead views of the strip that even extended to the suburbs beyond.The room was a study in understatement- tastefully decorated with teak accents, a bed and linens of regal quality, and a master bathroom with jacuzzi that borders on the cavernous. The off-strip location is ideal for those with a car who want to avoid the crush of strip traffic and be able to park within a minute or two of the hotels entrance. Try that at some of the 4,000 room strip megaliths. The buffet was good to very good depending on the night chosen, but the real standout--worth a detour in their own right--were the half-pound burgers at the 24/7 coffee shop. One drawback of note:literally inescapable music(of a volume disruptive enough to drown out my cellphone ringing) everywhere on the premises.Excluding the aforementioned caveat,this hotel has it all.	
