Sep 10 2005 	The Palms - A Great New Hotel Keeps Getting Better	The vibe at the Palms is contemporary, accessible, sexy, and comfortable. My room was clean, large, and yes the bed was very comfy. I had an upper floor room that had a great view of the strip, the mountains, and the city lights. There is a cafe and buffet, plus a variety of restaurants and a really good food court. Little Budda (Asian Food and Sushi) is awesome and so is the Mexican Restaurant. The staff at the reception desk is very professional and the Casino Floor is a relaxed place to do some gambling. They have a shuttle bus that will take you to the Strip, or it's an easy 5 minute drive if you have a car. The Ghost Bar is a rooftop bar and patio that has incredible views (admission is free early in the evening). The pool is nice and there's a spa if you're into pampering. Also, the Palms has almost finished a second hotel tower that will include a live music venue and more restaurants. A third tower (Palms Place) is planned for ultra luxurious condos that will increase the resort's hip quotient. The Palms is a very cool way to experience Las Vegas.	
Sep 9 2005	Good value	For $99 a night, this hotel was really a good value. Though the hotel is clearly off the strip, I was pleasantly suprised by the rooms and overall experience. The bathroom was large and fairly well lit, though there is only a tub/shower combination. The room itself was good size and the bed was very comfortable. The general color scheme of the rooms (with muted beige tones) was also pleasant. We did not have much problem with noise outside the room at night. The restaurants in the hotel are also of a high caliber. N9ne, for instance, was fantastic but extremely expensive. Unless you can get a better deal at one of the more spectacular strip hotels (e.g., Bellagio, Mandalay Bay, The Hotel, Wynn, or Venetian), I would not hesitate to recommend the Palms. (For instance, while I like the Bellagio better than the Palms, the Palms is a clear winner over the Monte Carlo.)	
