May 9 2005	Stay somewhere else	This is a tough one. While I would not ever recommend the Palms for an overnight stay, I do recommend that you visit the casino, steakhouse and the clubs, particularly the Ghost Bar. Why not stay? My experience:First, the room was not ready after the prescribed check-in time. They took my cell number and said that they would call when a &quot;room in your rate class&quot; is ready. I took it as a bad sign when they never called and indeed, my &quot;rate class&quot; ($400 per night) got me a room with a beautiful view of the air conditioning units on the roof, three bright spot lights right outside the window and a front seat to the construction of the Palms condos. I had requested a King bed and got two doubles. When I called and asked if a King room was available, I didn't get the runaround or any excuses and definitely no apologies, just a flat out &quot;no.&quot; You certainly don't go to Vegas to catch up on your sleep, and the Palms goes to great lengths to ensure that you don't sleep too late. It started my first morning when I thought someone was banging pipes right outside my window. Indeed, they were, at the construction site. Alllllllll morning long.I was awakened Saturday morning at 7 by a maid vacuuming right outside my door. It wasn't that the vaccum was particularly loud...it was her walkie-talkie turned at full volume so she could hear it over the vaccum's motor.I'm not sure exactly where they spent all the money building the Palms, but it certainly wasn't in their walls between guest rooms. I heard every cough (I am convinced the guy had emphysema), conversation and phone ring from the room next to mine. After a particular noisy spell (at 5:00 in the morning) my travel companion noted that the neighbors must have gone to sleep. I was able to inform her that they were not asleep and in fact had left the room...I had just heard them confirming on the phone that a car was picking them up. The worst was when they showered...it sounded like a water cannon being shot through a tin can between the walls. And each afternoon, we had to call housekeeping in order to get our room cleaned-up. The second time I called, I was informed that housekeeping works the rooms through 4:30 (or maybe 5)...saying, without really saying, that I needed to be patient. I would understand the need for patience except for the fact that I was calling at 5:30.I went to the Palms fully in the knowledge that it attracted a young crowd and that the hotel had a reputation for being a bit snobbish in the classic French model. Therefore, the loud, drunk meatheads yelling obsenities down the hall at 3:00 in the morning didn't really bother me. And I actually found the staff to be responsive and pleasant...very un-French like. But for $400 a night I expected a bit more from the hotel...no, a LOT more. My advice: Vist the Palms, stay somewhere else. P.S. In my business, I entertain a lot of clients at some of the most famous steakhouses in America. However, none -- not one -- even comes close to the dining experience at &quot;N9NE.&quot; The fantastic service was exceeded only by the food. If you go to Vegas and want a great, memorable meal, you must go to N9NE.	
