Feb 17 2005	Over -hyped	Don't believe the hype on this Las Vegas &quot;Resort&quot;. My wife and I stayed there for 5 days in January and were terribly disappointed. The Hotel caters to the young -money- has- no -value -crowd. If you are not a high roller or a celeb you are treated as if you should feel honored to be allowed on the property. The &quot;famous&quot;Ghost Bar is a joke in my opinion. $20 to get in and $8 for a bottle of beer....and the Secret Service wannbes that act as security personel are arrogant and rude. And the Rain Nightclub...more Secret Service wannbes that are rude and arrogant and so overpriced it makes Manhattan nightclubs seem inexpensive. The view from the Ghost Bar is nice, but like everything associated with this hotel..WAY OVER HYPED. Frankly, my wife and I have had better views from hotel rooms on the strip. The 9N Steakhouse is world class. A bit pricey but the service and quality of the food make this restaurant a wonderful dining experience. The staff at 9N should give the other hotel staff and &quot;security guards&quot; some lessons on hospitality and service. The other restaurants in the hotel are very good and the service is well above average. The dealers at the blackjack tables were cordial and some interacted very well with the players. We had fun at the tables. I can't report on the &quot;famous&quot; Skin Lounge or pool area as it was closed for the season, but we did visit the spa and fitness center. Again..pay to get in and frankly I've been in better equipped YMCA's and JCC's. Just a bunch of over-hyped fluff all the way around at this place. They normally charge $299 for a Deluxe Room with one king size bed. I have stayed in Holiday Inns for $80 that had better appointed rooms. My wife and I are in the upper income bracket and go to Vegas expecting to loose at the tables and spend like drunken sailors but we expect to be appreciated and made to feel good about dumping our money in a place. Folks, I strongly suggest you don't waste your money at the Palms. Mandalay Bay, Ceasars or just about all the other hotels on the strip will give you a better time for your money. When another hotel opens in Vegas that caters to this type crowd the Palms will be hosting Bingo conventions. For a romantic get-a-way with real class stay out at Lake Las Vegas at the newly opened Ritz. Even the Hyatt is nice, but a couple of clicks down from the Ritz in terms of overrall class and service.	
Feb 2 2005	2 baby boomers loved it	Although it seems that the Palms has a reputation for being the party spot for the twenty something crowd, my husband (52) and I (45) enjoyed our stay the week after Christmas very much. We were not among those lined up for the Ghost bar at 10 or 11 p.m., but we did enjoy the cafe in the morning for a reasonably priced breakfast each day. We encountered friendly and helpful staff throughout our 4 night stay. The room was clean and quiet with a very comfortable bed. The movie theater on site was a good alternative to the slots when we needed a break from gambling. The shuttle service to the mall and Ceasar's was a good start, but we would have liked for it to run more frequently and to have a couple more stops. Another nice thing we noticed: No pesky time share-type solicitations for &quot;free tickets&quot; if you listen to a presentation.	
Jan 14 2005	Hard Rock is better	I’m a huge fan of the Hard Rock Hotel, but we decided to give The Palms a try on one of our all-girls trips to Vegas last year because of its reputation. This place had some positives and negatives.Positives—the rooms are simply gorgeous. Understated elegance. That is the main reason I give this place an above average rating. Beds were unbelievably comfy, bathroom was beautiful and spacious with some great toiletries. Also, since The Palms is a smaller property, there is a more intimate feel to it. Easy walk to the pool, casino, restaurants, etc. The ghostbar is a blast, be sure to check it out, but the cover charge is a little ridiculous if you ask me.Negatives—the pool stinks. It is small and there is an unfriendly vibe. I’m used to the Hard Rock, where you hang out in the pool with a drink in your hand and make friends you wind up meeting up with again later that night! This pool scene just wasn’t any fun at all. Their 24-hour café wasn’t too great either. Head to the food court instead, you’re better off with a slice of pizza. Overall, the clientele and staff at the Hard Rock are just more fun and down-to-earth, but just as hot! I’ll visit The Palms for their clubs and restaurants (I really want to try N9NE!), but I most likely will not stay there again.	
