Nov 18 2004	Palms meets expectations	I stayed here mid-week in mid-November 2004. Check in and out went easily and quickly. The room itself was nice; call it upper-level Westin caliber. Bathroom spacious with cool lights that started dim, then got brighter (good for middle of the night trips).Design of the hotel was great, not gaudy as apparently some reviewers are looking for. Spa was good, good facilities (steam room, sauna, that shower that dumps water on you thing, jacuzzi, the usual gym equipment). Unfortunately, it was too chilly to enjoy the pool, but it looked nicely done. Went to the Ghostbar. Nice place, but in the end, it is just a nice bar, so the cover charge is a little silly. It's not like a huge club with light show or band or anything (not that it has to be, just that that's the type of place I would expect a cover). Also ate at Little Buddha which had a phenomenal interior, and pretty dang good food (although the menu was not quite as adventurous as I had hoped). If you stay at the Palms, and eat elsewhere, at least have a drink, or even just poke your head into Little Buddha. I gave this four stars, keeping in mind what it is: a trendy hotel off the Las Vegas strip. It’s no Ritz, nor did I expect it to be.	
